title:
Nonparametric efficient causal estimation of the intervention-specific
  expected number of recurrent events with continuous-time targeted maximum
  likelihood and highly adaptive lasso estimation

sections.text:
#### Abstract

Longitudinal settings involving outcome, competing risks and censoring events occurring and recurring in continuous time are common in medical research, but are often analyzed with methods that do not allow for taking post-baseline information into account. In this work, we define statistical and causal target parameters via the g-computation formula by carrying out interventions directly on the product integral representing the observed data distribution in a continuous-time counting process model framework. In recurrent events settings our target parameter identifies the expected number of recurrent events also in situations where the censoring mechanism depends on past information of post-baseline covariates such as the recurrent event process. We propose a flexible estimation procedure based on targeted maximum likelihood estimation coupled with highly adaptive lasso estimation for double robust and nonparametric inference for the considered target parameter. We illustrate our methods in a simulation study, and an application to a real data example.


Keywords: TMLE; Event history analysis; Causal inference; Double robust estimation; dataadaptive estimation.

# 1 Introduction 

Many problems of event history analysis and medical research involve outcome and censoring events occurring and recurring in continuous time. Recurrent events, specifically, refer to events that can occur multiple times for an individual over the duration of a study. Some examples include gastrointestinal infection in infants (Schnitzer et al., 2014), repeated hospital admissions (Kessing et al., 2004), or recurring lung exacerbations in cystic fibrosis patients (Miloslavsky et al., 2004). In this work, we consider nonparametric efficient and double robust estimation of a real-valued causal parameter in recurrent events settings characterized by baseline confounding, right-censoring and competing risks, particularly allowing for censoring mechanisms depending on the past of the recurrent event process.

Historically, two primary approaches have characterized the analysis of recurrent events (Cook and Lawless, 2007), one based on intensity models and another based on so-called marginal models. In intensity-based approaches (Cook and Lawless, 2002, 2007), models include different variations over summaries of information on previous events via time-dependent covariates (Prentice et al., 1981; Andersen and Gill, 1982; Aalen et al., 2004; Cook and Lawless, 2007), and the effect measures targeted are defined as hazard ratios obtained as regression coefficients. However, such hazard ratios do not attain a meaningful interpretation, both because hazard ratios generally suffer from lack of causal interpretability (Hernán, 2010; Martinussen et al., 2020) and because conditioning on post-treatment confounders blocks previous treatment effects (Robins, 1986). Although different approaches have been suggested to model the dependence among repeated events by modeling

intensities conditional on previous events via time-dependent covariates (see, e.g., Andersen and Gill, 1982; Aalen et al., 2004), it has generally been warned against conditioning on the number of past events (Cook and Lawless, 2007) as these are critical cases of post-randomization covariates. While frailty models (Vaupel et al., 1979) provide methods to incorporate heterogeneity without conditioning on the number of recurrent events, the hazard ratios derived from these models maintain only an individual-level interpretation and continue to lack causal interpretability (with certain model-specific exceptions for which there is in fact agreement between the two, see Hougaard, 2022). The other primary approach for analysis of recurrent events instead directly target the expected number (the marginal mean) of past recurrent events (Lawless and Nadeau, 1995; Cook and Lawless, 1997; Lin et al., 2000), estimation of which has for example been proposed carried out nonparametrically (Cook and Lawless, 1997), via regression modeling (Ghosh and Lin, 2002) or via pseudo-observations (Andersen et al., 2019; Furberg et al., 2021). In these proposals, however, post-baseline information is generally not included, and the often targeted nonparametric identification formula proposed by Cook and Lawless (1997) will not coincide with the (intervention-specific) expected number of recurrent events, involving marginalization over the entire observed process, unless censoring is independent. Particularly, such approaches do not allow right-censoring depending on the past of the recurrent event process, nor do they generalize to settings with time-dependent treatment interventions.

Developments in the field of causal inference, on the other hand, allow for correct adjustment for time-dependent confounders without blocking the effect of previous treatments mediated through time-dependent covariates (Robins, 1986, 1987, 1989b,a, 1992, 1998, 2000a,b; Bang and

Robins, 2005; Robins et al., 2008; van der Laan, 2010a,b; Petersen et al., 2014). Identification of causal parameters can be done via inverse probability weighting, such as done for recurrent events settings for example by Miloslavsky et al. (2004); Janvin et al. (2024), or, which is the route we pursue in this work, via the g-computation formula (Robins, 1986, 1987). The g-computation formula is defined as some characteristic of the post-interventional distribution obtained by carrying out hypothetical interventions directly on the distribution of the data factorized according to the time-ordering. We define our target parameter from the g-computation formula corresponding to the intervention-specific expected number of recurrent events, considering a counting process framework for the observed data, where the data-generating distribution is represented as a product of factors involving product integrals (Gill and Johansen, 1990; Andersen et al., 1993). For estimation, we apply targeted maximum likelihood estimation (van der Laan and Rubin, 2006; van der Laan and Rose, 2011) incorporating the efficient influence curve (Bickel et al., 1993) for the nonparametric model, combined with highly adaptive lasso estimation to flexibly account for dependence on, e.g., the follow-up information of the recurrent event process. To the best of our knowledge, our methods are the first to consider efficient nonparametric substitution estimation for causal parameters in recurrent event settings; the closest related work is Cortese and Scheike (2022) considering augmented inverse probability weighted estimation of the marginal mean. In contrast to their work, we target causal parameters under hypothetical treatment interventions and we do not make the standard assumption of independent censoring. Additionally, we verify double robustness properties, and present a different approach for nonparametric estimation under weak conditions on the statistical model. The recent and still unpublished work by Baer et al.

(2023) considers efficiency theory for a recurrent events setting as well. However, their approach omits consideration of the historical information on the recurrent event process, thereby limiting its ability to in fact address efficiency and constraining their methodology's applicability to real-world scenarios.

Our work extends and specializes the setting and methods considered by Rytgaard et al. (2022) by allowing for recurrent events outcomes; while the targeting procedures are closely related, Rytgaard et al. (2022) proposes a targeting procedure based on a combination of targeted maximum likelihood and sequential regression update steps, whereas we here work directly with the g-computation formula with direct plug-in estimation of clever covariates and the target parameter, and our targeting procedure involves only estimation and targeting of intensities. How to perform direct plug-in estimation, which involves estimation of complex conditional expectations across time, is an important topic of the present paper, that will not only benefit the analysis of recurrent events data but could potentially also be applied to enhance the estimation procedure proposed by Rytgaard et al. (2022).

There are two important components in the estimating procedure that we propose, including 1) the estimation of conditional intensities and 2) the algorithm to construct estimators for the conditional expectations (clever covariates) entering the efficient influence curve, as well as the target parameter, based on the estimators for the conditional intensities. Regarding 1), which is widely recognized in the recurrent events literature, it is a highly ambitious task to model the distribution of the entire recurrent events process, with high risk of model misspecification. In our approach we propose the use of highly adaptive lasso estimation (Benkeser and van der Laan,

2016; van der Laan, 2017), a nonparametric procedure which data-adaptively can learn about the dependence on past information in the data without specification of interaction or functional forms. While the highly adaptive lasso estimator has been implemented for hazards of time-to-first-event distributions (Rytgaard et al., 2023), with only baseline information beyond survival status, we here consider specifically the use of highly adaptive lasso estimator for intensities to learn about the dependence on the past of the recurrent event process. Concerning 2), we describe a matrixbased recursive scheme for direct plug-in evaluation, based on the interpretation of increments of continuous-time counting processes as binary variables with conditional probability distribution characterized by the corresponding conditional intensity increment (Andersen et al., 1993, Chapter IV.1.5). Essentially this involves replacing all differentials by differences or jumps, and the resulting estimation procedure is similar to how the classical Kaplan-Meier estimator (Kaplan and Meier, 1958) is formed as a finite product over discrete increments of the Nelson-Aalen estimator, or the Aalen-Johansen estimator (Aalen and Johansen, 1978) is formed as finite integral over causespecific hazard increments multiplied by the Kaplan-Meier estimator.

The article is organized as follows. Section 2 presents the statistical estimation setting, including the observed data and the observed data distribution. Section 3 defines the target parameter. The efficient influence curve is presented in Section 4, as well as the second-order remainder and its double robustness properties. Section 4.3 summarizes and presents results on nonparametric efficient inference for the presented targeted estimation procedure. Section 5 describes the proposed targeted maximum likelihood estimation procedure updating intensities for the recurrent event process and the death process. Section 6 describes estimation of conditional expectations

needed to evaluate the efficient influence curve and estimate the target parameter, and flexible estimation via the highly adaptive lasso of intensities depending on the history of the recurrent event process. Section 7 presents a simulation study for proof of concept and as a demonstration of the proposed methodology. Section 8 illustrates the methods with a literature dataset concerning readmissions for colorectal cancer patients. Section 9 closes with a discussion.

# 2 Setting and notation 

We consider a recurrent events data setting (Cook and Lawless, 2007; Andersen et al., 2019) as follows. Suppose $n \in \mathbb{N}$ subjects of population are followed in an interval of time $[0, \tau]$, each with observed data characterized by a multivariate counting process (Andersen et al., 1993) $\left(N^{y}, N^{d}, N^{c}\right)$ generating random times $T_{1}<\cdots<T_{R(\tau)}$ at which a recurrent outcome, the survival status and the censoring status may change. For example, $N^{y}$ could measure hospitalizations or number of strokes across time. We assume that, at baseline, covariates $L \in \mathbb{R}^{d}$ are measured, and then a treatment decision $A \in \mathcal{A}$, taking value in a finite set $\mathcal{A}$, is made. We collect the observed data for any individual $i$ in a bounded interval $[0, t] \subseteq[0, \tau]$ as follows

$$
\bar{O}_{i}(t)=\left(L_{i}, A_{i}, s, N_{i}^{y}(s), N_{i}^{d}(s), N_{i}^{c}(s): s \in\left\{\tilde{T}_{i, r}\right\}_{r=1}^{R_{i}(t)}\right)
$$

where $R_{i}(t)$ denotes the number of events experienced at time $t$. We let $\mathcal{F}_{t}=\sigma(\bar{O}(t))$ denote the $\sigma$-algebra generated by the observed data up until time $t$, and use $\Lambda$ to denote the cumulative intensity corresponding to the counting process $N$, so that, informally, $\mathbb{E}_{P_{0}}\left[N^{\cdot}(d t) \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right]=\Lambda_{0}(d t \mid$ $\mathcal{F}_{t-}$ ). Thus, $\Lambda_{0}^{y}$ denotes the non-terminal intensity of the counting process tracking recurrent events, $\Lambda_{0}^{d}$ denotes the intensity of the terminal death process, and $\Lambda_{0}^{c}$ denotes the intensity of

the terminal censoring process. Let $T^{d}$ denote the survival time and $T^{c}$ the censoring time, so that we observe $T^{\text {end }}=\min \left(T^{d}, T^{c}\right)$ and the indicator $\Delta=\mathbb{1}\left\{T^{d} \leq T^{c}\right\}$. We further let $T_{1}^{y}<T_{2}^{y}<\cdots$ denote the times of occurrences for the recurrent event. We thus have the observed times $\left(T_{1}, \ldots, T_{R(\tau)}\right)=\left(T_{1}^{y}, \ldots, T_{R(\tau)-1}^{y}, T^{\text {end }}\right)$, where $R(\tau)=1$ is allowed in which case there is only one observation at $T^{\text {end }}$, and $T_{1}^{y}, \ldots, T_{R(\tau)-1}^{y}=\emptyset$. The observed counting processes can also be represented as $N^{d}(t)=\mathbb{1}\left\{T^{\text {end }} \leq t, \Delta=1\right\} \in\{0,1\}, N^{c}(t)=\mathbb{1}\left\{T^{\text {end }} \leq t, \Delta=0\right\} \in\{0,1\}$ and $N^{y}(t)=\sum_{k} \mathbb{1}\left\{T_{k}^{y} \leq t, t \leq T^{\text {end }}\right\} \geq 0$, with $t \in[0, \tau], \tau>0$. We further denote by $\mu_{0}$ the density of the distribution of baseline covariates $L \in \mathbb{R}^{d}$ with respect to a dominating measure $\nu$, and by $\pi_{0}$ the distribution of the baseline treatment decision $A \in \mathcal{A}$, e.g., $\mathcal{A}=\{0,1\}$. The distribution $P_{0}$ of the observed data $O=\bar{O}(\tau)$ across the entire interval $[0, \tau]$ can then be represented generally as:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& d P_{0}(O)=\mu_{0}(L) d \nu(L) \pi_{0}(A \mid L) \\
& \int_{s \leq \tau}\left(\Lambda_{0}^{y}\left(d s \mid \mathcal{F}_{s-}\right)\right)^{N^{y}(d s)}\left(1-\Lambda_{0}^{y}\left(d s \mid \mathcal{F}_{s-}\right)\right)^{1-N^{y}(d s)} \\
& \int_{s \leq \tau}\left(\Lambda_{0}^{d}\left(d s \mid \mathcal{F}_{s-}\right)\right)^{N^{d}(d s)}\left(1-\Lambda_{0}^{d}\left(d s \mid \mathcal{F}_{s-}\right)\right)^{1-N^{d}(d s)} \\
& \int_{s \leq \tau}\left(\Lambda_{0}^{c}\left(d s \mid \mathcal{F}_{s-}\right)\right)^{N^{c}(d s)}\left(1-\Lambda_{0}^{c}\left(d s \mid \mathcal{F}_{s-}\right)\right)^{1-N^{c}(d s)}
\end{aligned}
$$

with $\mathcal{\Pi}$ denoting the product integral (Gill and Johansen, 1990). Note that the second factor $\mathcal{\Pi}_{s \leq \tau}\left(1-\Lambda_{0}\left(d s \mid \mathcal{F}_{s-}\right)\right)^{1-N^{\prime}(d s)}$ of each product integral evaluates to the exponential form $\exp \left(-\int_{0}^{\tau} \Lambda_{0}\left(d s \mid \mathcal{F}_{s-}\right)\right)$ when $\Lambda_{0}$ is continuous.

We further introduce notation for what we refer to as the interventional

$$
d G_{0}(O)=\pi_{0}(A \mid L) \prod_{s \leq \tau}\left(\Lambda_{0}^{c}\left(d s \mid \mathcal{F}_{s-}\right)\right)^{N^{c}(d s)}\left(1-\Lambda_{0}^{c}\left(d s \mid \mathcal{F}_{s-}\right)\right)^{1-N^{c}(d s)}
$$

and non-interventional

$$
\begin{gathered}
d Q_{0}(O)=\mu_{0}(L) d \nu(L) \prod_{s \leq \tau}\left(\Lambda_{0}^{y}\left(d s \mid \mathcal{F}_{s-}\right)\right)^{N^{y}(d s)}\left(1-\Lambda_{0}^{y}\left(d s \mid \mathcal{F}_{s-}\right)\right)^{1-N^{y}(d s)} \\
\prod_{s \leq \tau}\left(\Lambda_{0}^{d}\left(d s \mid \mathcal{F}_{s-}\right)\right)^{N^{d}(d s)}\left(1-\Lambda_{0}^{d}\left(d s \mid \mathcal{F}_{s-}\right)\right)^{1-N^{d}(d s)}
\end{gathered}
$$

parts of $P_{0}$, i.e., $d P_{0}=d Q_{0} d G_{0}$. We will also use $d G_{0, s}, d Q_{0, s}$ to denote the $s$-specific factors. We assume that $P_{0}$ belongs to a statistical model $\mathcal{M}$, where any $P \in \mathcal{M}$ can be parameterized as in (1) and factorized as in (2)-(3) into a non-interventional part $Q$ and an interventional part $G$, making only nonparametric assumptions for $Q$ but allowing semiparametric or parametric models for $G$. We will also use the notation $P=P_{Q, G}$, and $P_{0}=P_{Q_{0}, G_{0}}$ equivalently, to make the parametrization into the non-interventional and interventional parts explicit.

# 3 Target parameter 

We are generally interested in effects defined as parameters of the g-computation formula (Robins, 1986), corresponding to substituting a specific factor $G$ of $P \in \mathcal{M}$ by a user-supplied (or estimated) choice $G^{*}$. As specified in (2) above, $G$ involves the treatment distribution $\pi$ as well as the censoring mechanism $\Lambda^{c}$, and we shall be interested in substituting $G$ by $G^{*}$ consisting of the interventional $\Lambda^{c, *}\left(d t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right)=0$, putting all mass in no right-censoring, and an interventional distribution $\pi^{*}(a \mid L)$ for the treatment decision $A$ given covariates $L$. The latter could be, e.g., the degenerate

distribution $\pi^{*}(a \mid L)=\mathbb{1}\left\{a=a^{\prime}\right\}$ putting all mass in the fixed value $a^{\prime} \in \mathcal{A}$. We remark that any choice $G^{*}$ needs to satisfy the positivity assumption of absolute continuity, i.e., that $P^{G^{*}} \ll P$ for all $P \in \mathcal{M}$, which means for our purposes that

$$
\frac{1-N^{c}(\tau-)}{\int\left(t<\tau\left(1-\Lambda^{c}\left(d t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right)\right)\right.} \frac{\pi^{*}(a \mid L)}{\pi(a \mid L)}<\infty, \quad P-\text { a.s. for } a=0,1
$$

Note that this may also confine the choice of time horizon at which the target parameter is evaluated, as (4) implies that some individuals must remain uncensored by time $\tau$ for any possible observed level of history.

For a given choice $G^{*}$, we then define our target parameter $\Psi: \mathcal{M} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}_{+}$as the interventionspecific mean outcome of the number of recurrent events by time $\tau>0$, i.e.,

$$
\Psi(P)=\mathbb{E}_{P^{G^{*}}}\left[N^{y}(\tau)\right]
$$

where $\mathbb{E}_{P^{G^{*}}}$ denotes the expectation with respect to the g-computation formula $P^{G^{*}}=P_{Q, G^{*}}$. The targeted causal interpretation of (5) is that it represents the expected number of recurrent events if everyone had been treated according to the distribution $\pi^{*}$ and had there been no censoring. This holds under coarsening at random (CAR) on censoring with respect to the full data structure without right-censoring, and under conditional exchangeability with respect to treatment in a world without censoring. We address this more thoroughly in the Supplementary Material. We stress that the censoring mechanism is allowed to depend on the observed parts of the history, which contrasts with much of the recurrent events literature, where a stricter independent censoring assumption is commonly used (Cook and Lawless, 1997; Cortese and Scheike, 2022; Baer et al., 2023), requiring that censoring is independent of the death and the recurrent event processes, either marginally or only dependent on baseline information alone.

# 4 Nonparametric efficient estimation 

The efficient influence curve (Bickel et al., 1993; van der Vaart, 2000) for $\Psi: \mathcal{M} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}_{+}$under the nonparametric model $\mathcal{M}$ tells us about conditions under which we may construct $\sqrt{n}$-consistent and asymptotically linear estimators, also when data-adaptive estimators are employed for modeling the data-generating distribution through nuisance parameters. This relies on nuisance parameter estimators constructed such as to solve the efficient influence curve equation and to achieve asymptotic negligibility of an empirical process term and of a remainder term (van der Laan and Rubin, 2006; van der Laan and Rose, 2011, Theorem A.5). The basis is the so-called von Mises expansion of the functional $\Psi: \mathcal{M} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}_{+}, \Psi(P)-\Psi\left(P^{\prime}\right)=\int_{\mathcal{O}} \phi^{*}(P)(o) d\left(P-P^{\prime}\right)(o)+R\left(P, P^{\prime}\right)$, where $\phi^{*}(P)$ denotes the efficient influence curve, $R\left(P, P^{\prime}\right)=\Psi(P)-\Psi\left(P^{\prime}\right)+P^{\prime} \phi^{*}(P)$ denotes the mentioned remainder term, and $P, P^{\prime} \in \mathcal{M}$ are distributions in the statistical model $\mathcal{M}$. Note that $d P$ denotes integration with respect to the probability measure $P$ for the random variable $O$; we will also use the common operator notation $P h=\int h(o) d P(o)$ for functions $h: \mathcal{O} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$, and equivalently write $P h=\mathbb{E}_{P}[h(O)]$. In Section 4.1 we first present the efficient influence curve for our target parameter, in Section 4.2 we next present double robust properties, and in Section 4.3 we collect results and conditions for obtaining inference based on the efficient influence curve for our proposed estimator.

### 4.1 Efficient influence curve

We here present the efficient influence curve for estimating $\Psi: \mathcal{M} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}_{+}$in the nonparametric model $\mathcal{M}$. With the notation $\Delta N^{\prime}(t)=N^{\prime}(t)-N^{\prime}(t-)$, we define so-called clever covariates as

follows

$$
\begin{aligned}
& h_{t}^{d}\left(\Lambda^{d}, \Lambda^{y}\right)(O)=N^{y}(t-)-\mathbb{E}_{P^{G^{*}}}\left[N^{y}(\tau) \mid \Delta N^{d}(t)=0, \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right] \\
& h_{t}^{y}\left(\Lambda^{d}, \Lambda^{y}\right)(O)=\mathbb{E}_{P^{G^{*}}}\left[N^{y}(\tau) \mid \Delta N^{y}(t)=1, \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right]-\mathbb{E}_{P^{G^{*}}}\left[N^{y}(\tau) \mid \Delta N^{y}(t)=0, \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

and further clever weights as

$$
w_{t}\left(\pi, \Lambda^{c}\right)(O)=\frac{\pi^{*}(A \mid L)}{\pi(A \mid L) \mathcal{H}_{s<t}\left(1-\Lambda^{c}\left(d s \mid \mathcal{F}_{s-}\right)\right)}
$$

Then the efficient influence curve is given by

$$
\begin{aligned}
\phi^{*}(P)(O) & =\int_{t \leq \tau} \mathbb{1}\left\{T^{\mathrm{end}} \geq t\right\} w_{t}\left(\pi, \Lambda^{c}\right)(O) h_{t}^{d}\left(\Lambda^{d}, \Lambda^{y}\right)(O)\left(N^{d}(d t)-\Lambda^{d}\left(d t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right)\right) \\
& +\int_{t \leq \tau} \mathbb{1}\left\{T^{\mathrm{end}} \geq t\right\} w_{t}\left(\pi, \Lambda^{c}\right)(O) h_{t}^{y}\left(\Lambda^{d}, \Lambda^{y}\right)(O)\left(N^{y}(d t)-\Lambda^{y}\left(d t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right)\right) \\
& +\mathbb{E}_{P^{G^{*}}}\left[N^{y}(\tau) \mid L\right]-\Psi(P)
\end{aligned}
$$

The derivation can be found in the Supplementary Material.
4.1.1 Remark on the stricter independent censoring assumption. Consider the case that censoring is independent of the death and the recurrent event processes, either marginally or only dependent on baseline information. As remarked upon in Section 3, this is a common assumption in the analysis of recurrent events. Denote the corresponding statistical model by $\tilde{\mathcal{M}} \subset \mathcal{M}$. On the smaller model $\tilde{\mathcal{M}}$, a valid representation for the target parameter is

$$
\tilde{\Psi}(P)=\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} \sum_{a=0,1}\left(\int_{0}^{\tau} \tilde{S}^{d}(t-|a, \ell) \tilde{\Lambda}^{y}(d t \mid T^{\mathrm{end}} \geq t, a, \ell)\right) \pi^{*}(a \mid \ell) d \mu(\ell)
$$

with $\tilde{\Lambda}^{y}(d t \mid T^{\text {end }} \geq t, A, L)=\mathbb{E}_{P}\left[N^{y}(d t) \mid T^{\text {end }} \geq t, A, L\right]$ denoting the recurrent event rate (not intensity), and $\tilde{S}^{d}(t \mid a, \ell)=\mathcal{H}_{s \in(0, t]}\left(1-\Lambda^{d}(d s \mid T^{\text {end }} \geq s, a, \ell)\right)$ denoting the survival function

based on the death rate (not intensity) $\tilde{\Lambda}^{d}(d t \mid T^{\text {end }} \geq t, A, L)=\mathbb{E}_{P}\left[N^{d}(d t) \mid T^{\text {end }} \geq t, A, L\right]$. Note that plugging the Kaplan-Meier estimator for $\tilde{S}^{d}$ and the Nelson-Aalen estimator for $\tilde{\Lambda}^{y}$ (both stratified on $A$ ) into (12) corresponds to a stratified version of the nonparametric estimator initially proposed by Cook and Lawless (1997).

However, an estimator based directly on (12), not taking into account follow-up information on the recurrent event process, can only be locally efficient. This could for example be a TMLE based on working models $\tilde{\Lambda}^{d}, \tilde{\Lambda}^{y}$ for $\Lambda^{d}, \Lambda^{y}$ leaving out follow-up information on the recurrent process. With such working models, the clever covariates from Equation (6) and (7) reduce to $\tilde{h}_{t}^{y}\left(\Lambda^{d}, \Lambda^{y}\right)(O)=1$ and $\tilde{h}_{t}^{d}\left(\Lambda^{d}, \Lambda^{y}\right)(O)=-\frac{\int_{t}^{\tau} \tilde{S}^{d}(s-|A, L) \tilde{\Lambda}^{y}(d s \mid T^{\text {end }} \geq s, A, L)}{\tilde{S}^{d}(t \mid A, L)}$, and the working model based TMLE will agree with estimators starting with (12) rather than the full g-computation formula representation (5).

# 4.2 Double robustness properties 

The remainder from the von Mises expansion, defined as $R\left(P, P_{0}\right)=\Psi(P)-\Psi\left(P_{0}\right)+P_{0} \phi^{*}(P)$, plays a crucial role in understanding the double robustness properties of the estimation problem. In the Supplementary Material we show that

$$
\begin{gathered}
R\left(P, P_{0}\right)=\sum_{x=y, d} \mathbb{E}_{P_{0}^{G^{*}}}\left[\int_{0}^{\tau}\left(\frac{\pi_{0}(A \mid L) \prod_{s<t}\left(1-\Lambda_{0}^{c}\left(d s \mid \mathcal{F}_{s-}\right)\right)}{\pi(A \mid L) \prod_{s<t}\left(1-\Lambda^{c}\left(d s \mid \mathcal{F}_{s-}\right)\right)}-1\right)\left(1-N^{d}(t-\right)\right) \\
\times h_{t}^{x}\left(\Lambda^{d}, \Lambda^{y}\right)(O)\left(\Lambda_{0}^{x}\left(d t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right)-\Lambda^{x}\left(d t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right)\right)\right]
\end{gathered}
$$

This displays an important double robust structure, with direct implications for:

1. Double robustness in consistency. We have that $R\left(P, P_{0}\right)=0$ if either $\pi_{0}(a \mid \ell)=\pi(a \mid \ell)$ and $\prod_{s<t} \Lambda_{0}^{c}\left(d s \mid \mathcal{F}_{s-}\right)=\prod_{s<t} \Lambda^{c}\left(d s \mid \mathcal{F}_{s-}\right)$, or if $\Lambda_{0}^{d}\left(d t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right)=\Lambda^{d}\left(d t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right)$ and $\Lambda_{0}^{y}\left(d t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right)=$

$\Lambda^{y}\left(d t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right)$ for all $t \leq \tau$. Thus, consistent estimation can be achieved if consistent estimators are provided for either the censoring distribution and the treatment distribution, or for the intensities of the recurrent event and the death processes.
2. Rate double robustness. The double robust structure implies that the convergence rate of the second-order remainder can be bounded by a product of rates for the non-interventional and for the interventional parts, respectively. This implies, for example, that we have that $R\left(\hat{P}_{n}^{*}, P_{0}\right)=o_{P}\left(n^{-1 / 2}\right)$ for an estimator $\hat{P}_{n}^{*}$ when $\hat{P}_{n}^{*}$ consists of estimators for the nuisance parameters $\left(\Lambda^{y}, \Lambda^{d}, \Lambda^{c}, \pi\right)$ each estimating their true counterpart at a rate faster than $o_{P}\left(n^{-1 / 4}\right)$.

# 4.3 Inference for the targeted estimator 

Section 4.1 provides an expression for the efficient influence curve depending on the data-generating distribution through the nuisance parameters $\left(\Lambda^{y}, \Lambda^{d}, \Lambda^{c}, \pi\right)$. In Section 5 we use this directly to construct a targeted fluctuation procedure to update a set of initially given estimators for the nuisance parameters $\hat{P}_{n}=\left(\hat{\Lambda}_{n}^{y}, \hat{\Lambda}_{n}^{d}, \hat{\Lambda}_{n}^{c}, \hat{\pi}_{n}\right) \mapsto \hat{P}_{n}^{\text {tmle }}$ such as to solve the efficient influence curve equation,

$$
\mathbb{P}_{n} \phi^{*}\left(\hat{P}_{n}^{\mathrm{tmle}}\right)=o_{P}\left(n^{-1 / 2}\right)
$$

Note that $\mathbb{P}_{n}$ denotes the empirical distribution, such that $\mathbb{P}_{n} \phi^{*}\left(\hat{P}_{n}^{\text {tmle }}\right)=\frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} \phi^{*}\left(\hat{P}_{n}^{\text {tmle }}\right)\left(O_{i}\right)$. The targeted fluctuation procedure essentially amounts to a bias correction step, and is an important part of establishing asymptotic linearity. The proof (see, e.g., van der Laan and Rubin, 2006; van der Laan, 2017; Rytgaard et al., 2022; van der Laan and Rose, 2011, Theorem A.5) consists in evaluating the von Mises expansion in the estimator $\hat{P}_{n}^{\text {tmle }}$ and the true data-generating

$P_{0}$, and expanding this into a sum including multiple terms that need to be asymptotic negligible, one corresponding to the efficient influence curve equation, one to an empirical process term, and one to the second-order remainder. Combined with highly adaptive lasso estimation, we need the following conditions to hold. We emphasize, as we will return to later, that these conditions impose much weaker assumptions than what is needed to rely on (semi)parametric modeling.

Assumption 1. For any $P \in \mathcal{M}$ the nuisance parameters $\left(\Lambda^{y}, \Lambda^{d}, \Lambda^{c}, \pi\right)$ can be parametrized by càdlàg (i.e., right-continuous with left limits) functions with finite sectional variation norm, and $\left(\Lambda^{c}, \pi\right)$ together with the choice $\tau>0$ further fulfill the (strong) positivity assumption that $\mathcal{J}_{t<\tau}\left(1-\Lambda^{c}\left(d t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right)\right) \pi(a \mid L)>\eta>0$, a.e., for $a=0,1$.

Under Assumption 1 it holds for an estimator $\hat{P}_{n}^{\text {tmle }}$ fulfilling (13), when the estimators for the nuisance parameters are constructed such as to achieve at least $n^{-1 / 4}$ convergence (such as with highly adaptive lasso estimation), that the TMLE estimator $\hat{\psi}_{n}^{\text {tmle }}=\Psi\left(\hat{P}_{n}^{\text {tmle }}\right)$ for the target parameter is asymptotically linear with influence function equal to the efficient influence curve, $\sqrt{n}\left(\hat{\psi}_{n}^{\text {tmle }}-\Psi\left(P_{0}\right)\right)=\sqrt{n} \mathbb{P}_{n} \phi^{*}\left(P_{0}\right)+o_{P}\left(n^{-1 / 2}\right)$. From this it directly follows that $\sqrt{n}\left(\Psi\left(\hat{P}_{n}^{\text {tmle }}\right)-\right.$ $\left.\Psi\left(P_{0}\right)\right) \xrightarrow{\mathcal{P}} N\left(0, P_{0} \phi^{*}\left(P_{0}\right)^{2}\right)$, and inference for $\hat{\psi}_{n}^{\text {tmle }}$ follows.

# 5 Targeted maximum likelihood estimation 

Targeted maximum likelihood proceeds by fluctuating initial estimators by maximizing the likelihood in a targeted direction such as to solve the efficient influence curve equation. In our case, the entire data-generating distribution is parameterized by intensities, and we can carry out targeting according to the log-likelihood loss function and least favorable submodel presented by Rytgaard

et al. (2022, Section 5.2), which was similarly applied for competing risks settings in Rytgaard et al. (2023).

For the recurrent event specific and the death specific cumulative intensities $\Lambda^{y}, \Lambda^{d}$ with corresponding intensity processes $\lambda^{y}, \lambda^{d}$, we define the intercept-only submodel $(x=y, d)$

$$
\Lambda_{\varepsilon}^{x}\left(d t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right)=\Lambda^{x}\left(d t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right) \exp (\varepsilon), \quad \varepsilon \in \mathbb{R}
$$

and further the log-likelihood loss function

$$
\mathscr{L}_{x}\left(\Lambda^{x}\right)(O)=\int_{0}^{\tau} w_{t}\left(\pi, \Lambda^{c}\right)(O)(O) h_{t}^{x}\left(\Lambda^{d}, \Lambda^{y}\right)(O)\left(\log \lambda^{x}\left(t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right) N^{x}(d t)-\Lambda^{x}\left(d t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right)\right)
$$

It is straightforward to show that this pair has the desired property that

$$
\left.\frac{d}{d \varepsilon}\right|_{\varepsilon=0} \mathscr{L}_{x}\left(\Lambda_{\varepsilon}^{x}\right)(O)=\int_{0}^{\tau} w_{t}\left(\pi, \Lambda^{c}\right)(O)(O) h_{t}^{x}\left(\Lambda^{d}, \Lambda^{y}\right)(O)\left(N^{x}(d t)-\Lambda^{x}\left(d t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right)\right)
$$

We note that alternative versions are also possible, where the clever covariate and/or the clever weight, are included as a (clever) covariate in the fluctuation model in the submodel, rather than used as (clever) weights in the loss function.

# 5.1 Targeting procedure 

Our targeting procedure consists of the following:

1. Initial estimation. Estimators $\hat{\Lambda}_{n}^{c}$ and $\hat{\pi}_{n}$ for $\Lambda^{c}$ and $\pi$, based on which we get an estimator for $w_{t}\left(\pi, \Lambda^{c}\right)$ as:

$$
w_{t}\left(\hat{\pi}_{n}, \hat{\Lambda}_{n}^{c}\right)(O)=\frac{\pi^{*}(A \mid L)}{\hat{\pi}_{n}(A \mid L) \prod_{s<t}\left(1-\hat{\Lambda}_{n}^{c}\left(d s \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right)\right)}
$$

Furthermore, initial estimators $\hat{\Lambda}_{n}^{d}$ and $\hat{\Lambda}_{n}^{y}$ for $\Lambda^{d}$ and $\Lambda^{y}$, based on which we also estimate $h_{t}^{d}\left(\Lambda^{d}, \Lambda^{y}\right)$ and $h_{t}^{y}\left(\Lambda^{d}, \Lambda^{y}\right)$; while the latter is straightforward if estimators $\hat{\Lambda}_{n}^{d}$ and $\hat{\Lambda}_{n}^{y}$ are based on working models leaving out follow-up information on the recurrent process (see Section 4.1.1), it is much more subtle for the general case. This is the topic of Section 6.
2. Targeting. A targeting procedure to update $\Lambda^{d}$ and $\Lambda^{y}$. We propose to execute this in an iterative manner starting with $\hat{\Lambda}_{n, 0}^{d}:=\hat{\Lambda}_{n}^{d}$ and $\hat{\Lambda}_{n, 0}^{y}:=\hat{\Lambda}_{n}^{y}$, and the $m$ th step proceeding as follows:

Update $\hat{\Lambda}_{n, m}^{d} \mapsto \hat{\Lambda}_{n, m+1}^{d}$ along the parametric submodel (14) to solve the relevant term (9) equal to zero for given $w_{t}\left(\hat{\Lambda}_{n}^{c}, \hat{\pi}_{n}\right), h_{t}^{d}\left(\hat{\Lambda}_{n, m}^{d}, \hat{\Lambda}_{n, m}^{y}\right)$ and $h_{t}^{y}\left(\hat{\Lambda}_{n, m}^{d}, \hat{\Lambda}_{n, m}^{y}\right)$.

Update $\hat{\Lambda}_{n, m}^{y} \mapsto \hat{\Lambda}_{n, m+1}^{y}$ along the parametric submodel (14) to solve the relevant term (10) equal to zero for given $w_{t}\left(\hat{\Lambda}_{n}^{c}, \hat{\pi}_{n}\right), h_{t}^{d}\left(\hat{\Lambda}_{n, m}^{d}, \hat{\Lambda}_{n, m}^{y}\right)$ and $h_{t}^{y}\left(\hat{\Lambda}_{n, m}^{d}, \hat{\Lambda}_{n, m}^{y}\right)$.

This procedure is repeated until $\left|\mathbb{P}_{n} \phi\left(\hat{P}_{n}^{*}\right)\right| \leq s_{n}$, where $\hat{P}_{n}^{*}=\left(\hat{\Lambda}_{n}^{y\left(m^{*}\right)}, \hat{\Lambda}_{n}^{d\left(m^{*}\right)}, \hat{\Lambda}_{n}^{c}, \hat{\pi}_{n}\right)$ and $s_{n}=$ $\sqrt{\mathbb{P}_{n}\left(\phi\left(\hat{P}_{n}\right)\right)^{2}} /\left(n^{-1 / 2} \log n\right)$ with $\mathbb{P}_{n}\left(\phi\left(\hat{P}_{n}\right)\right)^{2}$ estimating the variance of the efficient influence function based on the collection of initial estimators for the nuisance parameters $\hat{P}_{n}=\left(\hat{\Lambda}_{n}^{y}, \hat{\Lambda}_{n}^{d}, \hat{\Lambda}_{n}^{c}, \hat{\pi}_{n}\right)$.

# 6 Clever covariate estimation 

The clever covariates from Equations (6) and (7) presented in Section 4.1 require evaluation of the conditional expectations $\mathbb{E}_{P^{G^{*}}}\left[N^{y}(\tau) \mid \Delta N^{d}(t)=0, T^{\text {end }} \geq t, \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right], \mathbb{E}_{P^{G^{*}}}\left[N^{y}(\tau) \mid \Delta N^{y}(t)=\right.$ $\left.1, T^{\text {end }} \geq t, \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right]$ and $\mathbb{E}_{P^{G^{*}}}\left[N^{y}(\tau) \mid \Delta N^{y}(t)=0, T^{\text {end }} \geq t, \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right]$ under the g-computation formula. In Section 6.1, we describe a plug-in approach based on a matrix-based recursion scheme for direct evaluation of the g-computation formula; in Section 6.2 we then describe the incorporation, and

particular utility, of highly adaptive lasso estimation for estimation of the conditional intensities.

We shall overall move forward with Andersen-Gill type multiplicative models (Andersen and Gill, 1982; Andersen et al., 1993) for $x=y, d, c$ as follows:

$$
\Lambda^{x}\left(d t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right)=\lambda^{x}\left(t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right) d t=\mathbb{1}\left\{T^{\mathrm{end}} \geq t\right\} \lambda_{\mathrm{fd}}^{x}(t) \exp \left(f^{x}(t, \rho\left(\bar{N}^{y}(t-)\right), A, L)\right) d t
$$

where $\lambda_{\mathrm{fd}}^{y}, \lambda_{\mathrm{fd}}^{d}, \lambda_{\mathrm{fd}}^{c}$ are unspecified baseline hazards, and $f^{y}, f^{d}, f^{c}$ are functions of time $t$, treatment $A$ and covariates $L$ as well as the past of the recurrent event process $\bar{N}^{y}(t-)=\left(N^{y}(s): s<t\right)$ via a summary function $\rho$. We remark that the baseline intensities may also be collapsed into $f^{y}, f^{d}$ and $f^{c}$. The function $\rho$ expresses what kind of summaries of $\bar{N}^{y}(t-)$ that $f^{y}, f^{d}, f^{c}$ may depend on, whereas $f^{y}, f^{d}, f^{c}$ specify functional forms and interactions with time, treatment or covariates. We assume that $\rho$ is fixed a priori, while $f^{y}, f^{d}$ and $f^{c}$ may be data-adaptively learned from the data, e.g., by highly adaptive lasso estimation as we return to in Section 6.2. To reflect the potential data-adaptivity, we will use the notation $f_{n}$. Note also that $\rho$ need not be a fixed model assumption, and that multiple HAL estimators with different choices of $\rho$ are possible.

# 6.1 Analytic evaluation of the g-computation formula 

Throughout this section, we denote the ordered observed event times across all subjects by

$$
0=T_{(0)}<T_{(1)}<\cdots<T_{(K)} \leq \tau
$$

and we use the shorthand notation $\bar{O}_{(k)}=\bar{O}\left(T_{(k)}\right), \mathcal{F}_{k}=\sigma\left(\bar{O}_{(k)}\right)$ and $\mathcal{F}_{k-}=\sigma\left(\bar{O}\left(T_{(k)}^{-}\right)\right)$, for $k=1, \ldots, K$. For the following, we consider discrete cumulative intensities $\Lambda^{\cdot}$ that have jumps where $N^{\cdot}$ does. The distribution of increments $\Delta N^{\cdot}\left(T_{(k)}\right)$ given the past up till time $T_{(k)}$ can

be characterized by $\Delta \Lambda^{\prime}\left(T_{(k)} \mid \mathcal{F}_{k-}\right)$, and we shall construct an estimation procedure for the clever covariates based on sequentially integrating out the 'binary variables' corresponding to increments $\Delta N^{\prime}\left(T_{(k)}\right)$. In the Supplementary Material we exemplify how this process yields wellknown formulas in the point-treatment survival and competing risks settings, as well as a recurrent event setting where intensities do not depend on the history of the recurrent event process.

We emphasize that the discreteness of the cumulative intensities $\Lambda^{\prime}$ does not reflect an assumption of the parameter space, but is used rather to reflect the discreteness of estimators. For example, when $\Lambda^{\prime}$ is estimated by a Nelson-Aalen estimator (Johansen, 1978), it will indeed be a step function with increments at the observed jump times. Likewise this is the case when estimation is based on a Cox model combined with a Breslow estimator for the cumulative baseline hazard (Breslow, 1974). When we proceed to highly adaptive lasso estimation in Section 6.2, with the implementation based on a penalized Poisson regression approach, the increments of cumulative intensities over intervals $\left[T_{(k)}, T_{(k+1)}\right]$ are obtained by multiplying the intensity rate at time $T_{(k)}$ by the length of the interval $\left(T_{(k)}, T_{(k+1)}\right]$.
6.1.1 Piecewise constant dependence on the recurrent event process The crucial part for developing the following estimators for the clever covariates comes down to the number of (finitely many) different possible paths that we need to integrate out over. This is determined by $f_{n}$, and what we ultimately need is that $f_{n}\left(t, \rho\left(\bar{N}^{y}(t-)\right), a, \ell\right)$ varies as a piecewise constant function of its argument $\bar{N}^{y}(t-)$. Then we can partition the sample space of $\bar{N}^{y}(t-)$ into cubes

$\omega_{j \in \mathscr{J}} \mathcal{N}_{j}$ for a finite index set $\mathscr{J}$, such that

$$
f_{n}\left(t, \rho\left(\bar{N}_{1}^{y}(t-)\right), a, \ell\right)=f_{n}\left(t, \rho\left(\bar{N}_{2}^{y}(t-)\right), a, \ell\right), \quad \text { for all } \bar{N}_{1}^{y}(t-), \bar{N}_{2}^{y}(t-) \in \mathcal{N}_{j}
$$

for fixed $t, a, \ell, j$. Note that $f_{n}$ is allowed to vary more generally in its remaining arguments.
There are different ways to achieve this piecewise constant dependence. It is for example ensured for any $f_{n}$ when $\rho$ is simply fixed beforehand so that it maps $\bar{N}^{y}(t-)$ to simple categorical variables, such as, for example, $\rho\left(\bar{N}^{y}(t-)\right)=\mathbb{1}\left\{N^{y}(t-) \geq 1\right\}$ (any events in the past), or $\rho\left(\bar{N}^{y}(t-)\right)=N^{y}(t-)$ (number of events in the past). More generally it is ensured when $f_{n}$ is obtained with the highly adaptive lasso estimator, which by construction depends on covariates through a linear combination of zero-order spline basis functions. Then, even if $\rho\left(\bar{N}^{y}(t-)\right)$ should depend more generally on $\bar{N}^{y}(t-)$, there will still be a partitioning $\omega_{j \in \mathscr{J}} \mathcal{N}_{j}$ of the sample space of $\bar{N}^{y}(t-)$ such that (16) holds.
6.1.2 Evaluation of the g-computation formula and clever covariates We shall here use $\Delta \Lambda_{k, j^{\prime}}(a, L)$ to denote the time $T_{(k)}$-increment of the intensity $\Lambda^{\cdot}$ evaluated in the histories up till time $T_{(k-1)}$ that are consistent with index $j$, i.e.,

$$
\Delta \Lambda_{k, j}(a, L)=\Delta \Lambda^{\cdot}\left(T_{(k)} \mid T^{\mathrm{end}} \geq T_{(k)}, \bar{N}^{y}\left(T_{(k-1)}\right) \in \mathcal{N}_{j}, A=a, L\right)
$$

Similarly, we define objects

$$
Z_{k+1, j}(a, L)=\mathbb{E}_{P^{G^{*}}}\left[N^{y}(\tau)-N^{y}\left(T_{(k+1)}\right) \mid \bar{N}^{y}\left(T_{(k)}\right) \in \mathcal{N}_{j}, T^{\mathrm{end}} \geq T_{(k+1)}, A=a, L\right]
$$

which are the conditional expectations under the g-computation formula with the conditioned history prior to time $T_{(k)}$ being consistent with index $j$. Note that we have $Z_{K-1, j}(a, L)=$

$\Delta \Lambda_{K, j}^{y}(a, L)$, and that $Z_{0, j}(a, L)=\mathbb{E}_{P^{G^{*}}}\left[N^{y}(\tau) \mid A=a, L\right]$ irrespective of $j$. We here focus the presentation on the case that $\rho\left(\bar{N}^{y}(t-)\right)=\min \left(N^{y}(t-), J-1\right)$, for which $j \in\{1,2, \ldots, J\}$ marks that $N^{y}(t-)=j-1$. The presentation for general $\rho\left(\bar{N}^{y}(t-)\right)$ can be found in the Supplementary Material together with the proof of the following procedure for evaluating the conditional expectations $\boldsymbol{Z}_{k}(a, L)=\left(Z_{k, j}(a, L): j \in \mathscr{J}\right) \in \mathbb{R}^{J \times 1}$ from $\boldsymbol{Z}_{k+1}(a, L)$. Denote by $\boldsymbol{Z}_{k}(a, L)=$ $\left(Z_{k, j}(a, L): j \in \mathscr{J}\right) \in \mathbb{R}^{J \times 1}$, and define the augmented $\tilde{\boldsymbol{Z}}_{k}(a, L)=\left(\boldsymbol{Z}_{k}(a, L), 1\right) \in \mathbb{R}^{(J+1) \times 1}$. For all $a, L$, we have that:

$$
\tilde{\boldsymbol{Z}}_{k}(a, L)=\tilde{\boldsymbol{B}}_{k}(a, L) \tilde{\boldsymbol{Z}}_{k+1}(a, L)
$$

for a matrix $\tilde{\boldsymbol{B}}_{k}(a, L) \in \mathbb{R}^{(J+1) \times(J+1)}$ with elements (suppressing the dependence on $a, L$ ), for $j=1, \ldots, J-1, \tilde{\boldsymbol{B}}_{k, j, j}=\left(1-\Delta \Lambda_{k, j}^{d}\right)\left(1-\Delta \Lambda_{k, j}^{y}\right), \tilde{\boldsymbol{B}}_{k, j, j+1}=\tilde{\boldsymbol{B}}_{k, j, J+1}=\tilde{\boldsymbol{B}}_{k, J, J+1}=\left(1-\Delta \Lambda_{k, j}^{d}\right) \Delta \Lambda_{k, j}^{y}$, for $j=J, \tilde{\boldsymbol{B}}_{k, j, j}=\left(1-\Delta \Lambda_{k, j}^{d}\right)$, and with $\tilde{\boldsymbol{B}}_{k, J+1, J+1}=1$, and $\tilde{\boldsymbol{B}}_{k, j, l}=0$ otherwise. We also have that:

$$
h_{T_{(k)}}^{d}\left(\Lambda^{d}, \Lambda^{y}\right)(O)=\tilde{\boldsymbol{b}}_{k}^{d}(a, L) \tilde{\boldsymbol{Z}}_{k+1}(a, L)
$$

where $\tilde{\boldsymbol{b}}_{k}^{d}(a, L) \in \mathbb{R}^{1 \times(J+1)}$ has all entries equal to zero except $\tilde{\boldsymbol{b}}_{k, J+1}^{d}=-\Delta \Lambda_{k, j\left(\bar{O}_{(k-1)}\right)}^{y}$, and, for $j\left(\bar{O}_{(k-1)}\right) \leq J-1, \tilde{\boldsymbol{b}}_{k, j\left(\bar{O}_{(k-1)}\right)+1}^{d}=-\Delta \Lambda_{k, j\left(\bar{O}_{(k-1)}\right)}^{y}$ and $\tilde{\boldsymbol{b}}_{k, j\left(\bar{O}_{(k-1)}\right)}^{d}=-\left(1-\Delta \Lambda_{k, j\left(\bar{O}_{(k-1)}\right)}^{y}\right)$, and, for $j\left(\bar{O}_{(k-1)}\right)=J, \tilde{\boldsymbol{b}}_{k, J}^{d}=-1$. Here $j\left(\bar{O}_{(k-1)}\right)$ is the index consistent the observed history $\bar{O}_{(k-1)}$ of $O$. Likewise we have:

$$
h_{T_{(k)}}^{y}\left(\Lambda^{d}, \Lambda^{y}\right)(O)=\tilde{\boldsymbol{b}}_{k}^{y}(a, L) \tilde{\boldsymbol{Z}}_{k+1}(a, L)
$$

where $\tilde{\boldsymbol{b}}_{k}^{y}(a, L) \in \mathbb{R}^{1 \times(J+1)}$ has all entries equal to zero except $\tilde{\boldsymbol{b}}_{k, J+1}^{y}=1$, and, for $j\left(\bar{O}_{(k-1)}\right) \leq J-1$, $\tilde{\boldsymbol{b}}_{k, j\left(\bar{O}_{(k-1)}\right)+1}^{y}=1$ and $\tilde{\boldsymbol{b}}_{k, j\left(\bar{O}_{(k-1)}\right)}^{y}=-1$.

# 6.2 Highly adaptive lasso estimation 

As previously presented, we consider intensities on the form

$$
\Lambda^{\prime}\left(d t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right)=\lambda^{\prime}\left(t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right) d t=\mathbb{1}\left\{T^{\mathrm{end}} \geq t\right\} \exp \left(f^{\prime}\left(t, \rho\left(\bar{N}^{y}(t-)\right), A, L\right)\right) d t
$$

with the only difference compared to (15) being that we have collapsed the baseline hazard from the models presented into $f^{\prime}$. As noted, then examples of $\rho$ include dependence on $\bar{N}^{y}(t-)=$ $\left(N^{y}(s): s<t\right)$ through, for example, $\mathbb{1}\left\{N^{y}(t-) \geq 1\right\}$ (any jumps in the past), or $N^{y}(t-)$ (number of jumps in the past). How the dependence plays out, is further determined by $f$. In this section we will use notation as follows:

$$
X=(L, A) \in \mathcal{X} \subset \mathbb{R}^{d+1}, \quad V=\rho\left(\bar{N}^{y}(t-)\right) \in \mathcal{V} \subset \mathbb{R}^{d^{\prime}}
$$

We then define partitionings $\mathcal{X}=\cup_{m} \mathcal{X}_{m}$ and $\mathcal{V}=\cup_{m} \mathcal{V}_{m}$ into cubes $\mathcal{X}_{m}$ and $\mathcal{V}_{m}$, and let $x_{m} \in \mathcal{X}_{m}$ and $v_{m} \in \mathcal{V}_{m}$ denote left endpoints of the cubes $\mathcal{X}_{m}$ and $\mathcal{V}_{m}$, respectively. We further introduce indicator basis functions: $\phi_{r}(t)=\mathbb{1}\left\{t_{r} \leq t\right\} ; \phi_{m, \mathcal{S}}(x)=\mathbb{1}\left\{x_{m, \mathcal{S}} \leq x_{\mathcal{S}}\right\}$ for a subset of indices $\mathcal{S} \subset\{1, \ldots, d+1\}$; and $\phi_{m, \mathcal{S}}^{\prime}(v)=\mathbb{1}\left\{v_{m, \mathcal{S}} \leq v_{\mathcal{S}}\right\}$ for a subset of indices $\mathcal{S} \subset\left\{1, \ldots, d^{\prime}\right\}$. Here $x_{m, \mathcal{S}}$ and $x_{\mathcal{S}}$ denote $\mathcal{S}$-specific coordinates of $x_{m}$ and $x$, respectively, and $v_{m, \mathcal{S}}$ and $v_{\mathcal{S}}$ likewise denote $\mathcal{S}$-specific coordinates of $v_{m}$ and $v$. Consider for example the case that $V=\rho\left(\bar{N}^{y}(t-)\right)=$ $N^{y}(t-) \in \mathcal{V} \subset\{0,1, \ldots\}$. Then $\mathcal{V}=\cup_{m}\left[v_{m}, v_{m}+1\right)$ defines a partitioning into disjoint intervals $\mathcal{V}_{m}=\left[v_{m}, v_{m}+1\right)$, and the corresponding indicator basis functions are $\phi_{m}^{\prime}(v)=\mathbb{1}\left\{v_{m} \leq v\right\}$.

Denoting by $\sum_{\mathcal{S}}$ the sum of all subsets $\mathcal{S}$ of indices, and by $\sum_{m}$ the sum over partitionings, the approximation $f_{\beta}$ of $f^{\prime}$ with support over the endpoints of the partitionings now admits a

representation over indicator basis functions as follows

$$
\begin{aligned}
& f_{\beta}(t, v, x)=\sum_{r=0}^{R} \phi_{r}(t) \beta_{r}+\sum_{r=0}^{R} \sum_{\mathcal{S} \subset\{1, \ldots, d+1\}} \sum_{m} \phi_{r}(t) \phi_{m, \mathcal{S}}(x) \beta_{r, m, \mathcal{S}} \\
&+\sum_{r=0}^{R} \sum_{\mathcal{S} \subset\{1, \ldots, d^{\prime}\}} \sum_{m} \phi_{r}(t) \phi_{m, \mathcal{S}}^{\prime}(v) \beta_{r, m, \mathcal{S}}^{\prime} \\
&+\sum_{r=0}^{R} \sum_{\mathcal{S} \subset\{1, \ldots, d+1\}} \sum_{\mathcal{S}^{\prime} \subset\{1, \ldots, d^{\prime}\}} \sum_{m} \sum_{m^{\prime}} \phi_{r}(t) \phi_{m, \mathcal{S}}(x) \phi_{m^{\prime}, \mathcal{S}^{\prime}}^{\prime}(v) \beta_{r, m, \mathcal{S}, m^{\prime}, \mathcal{S}^{\prime}} .
\end{aligned}
$$

Here, the $\beta$ coefficients represent pointmass assigned by $f_{\beta}$ to its support points. One may note that the dependence of $f_{\beta}$ on $V=\rho\left(\bar{N}^{y}(t-\})\right.$ plays out through (19) (main effects, and interactions with time) and (20) (all interactions), and that there are only finitely many ways in which $f_{\beta}$ can depend on the history of the recurrent event process (even when $V$, or part of $V$, is continuous). This all fits into the estimation and implementation framework described in Section 6.1. The sectional variation norm (Gill et al., 1995; van der Laan, 2017) of $f_{\beta}$ becomes a sum over the absolute values of its coefficients, i.e., it equals the $L_{1}$-norm of the coefficient vector. We can now define the highly adaptive lasso estimator as an empirical risk minimizer $\hat{f}_{n}=f_{\hat{\beta}_{n}}$, defined as $\hat{\beta}_{n}=\underset{\beta}{\operatorname{argmin}} \mathbb{P}_{n} \mathscr{L}\left(f_{\beta}\right)$, s.t. $\|\beta\|_{1} \leq \mathscr{M}$, with the log-likelihood loss $\mathscr{L}(\Lambda^{\cdot})(O)=-\int_{0}^{\tau} \log \lambda\left(t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right) N^{\cdot}(d t)+\int_{0}^{\tau} \Lambda^{\cdot}(d t \mid$ $\left.\mathcal{F}_{t-}\right)$. Following Rytgaard et al. (2023), this can be implemented as an $L_{1}$-penalized Poisson regression with the indicator functions $\phi_{r}(t), \phi_{r}(t) \phi_{\mathcal{S}, m}(x), \phi_{r}(t) \phi_{\mathcal{S}^{\prime}, m^{\prime}}^{\prime}(v)$ and $\phi_{r}(t) \phi_{\mathcal{S}, m}(x) \phi_{\mathcal{S}^{\prime}, m^{\prime}}^{\prime}(v)$ as covariates and $\beta_{r}, \beta_{r, \mathcal{S}, m}, \beta_{r, \mathcal{S}^{\prime}, m^{\prime}}^{\prime}, \beta_{r, \mathcal{S}, m, \mathcal{S}^{\prime}, m^{\prime}}$ as the corresponding coefficients.

# 7 Simulation study 

We consider a simulation study to demonstrate the proposed methodology and as a proof of concept. We explore a setting in which all intensity processes are allowed to depend on the recurrent

event process in a simple manner, and compare our TMLE estimator to an unadjusted nonparametric estimator, as well as a simplified version of TMLE including only baseline information (with simple plug-in estimation of the target parameter and of clever covariates, c.f., Section 4.1.1).

Let $L_{1} \sim \operatorname{Unif}(-1,1), L_{2} \sim \operatorname{Unif}(0,1)$ and $L_{3} \sim \operatorname{Unif}(0,1)$, and let $A \in\{0,1\}$ be randomized with $P(A=1)=1-P(A=0)=0.5$. Recurrent events are simulated according to the multiplicative intensity model

$$
\lambda^{y}\left(t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right)=\lambda_{\text {baseline }}^{y}(t) \exp \left(\alpha^{y}+\beta_{A}^{y} A+\beta_{L_{1}}^{y} L_{1}^{2}+\beta_{N^{y}}^{y} \mathbb{1}\left\{N^{y}(t-) \geq 1\right\}\right)
$$

where $\beta_{N^{y}}^{y}$ controls the dependence on whether there were any past recurrent events. Likewise, censoring events are simulated according to the intensity model

$$
\lambda^{c}\left(t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right)=\lambda_{\text {baseline }}^{c}(t) \exp \left(\alpha^{c}+\beta_{A}^{c} A+\beta_{L_{1}}^{c} L_{1}+\beta_{N^{y}}^{c} \mathbb{1}\left\{N^{y}(t-) \geq 1\right\}\right)
$$

where, like above, $\beta_{N^{y}}^{c}$ controls the dependence on whether there were any past recurrent events. Finally, failure events are simulated according to the intensity model

$$
\lambda^{d}\left(t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-}\right)=\lambda_{\text {baseline }}^{d}(t) \exp \left(\alpha^{d}+\beta_{A}^{d} A+\beta_{L_{1}}^{d} L_{1}+\beta_{N^{y}}^{d} \mathbb{1}\left\{N^{y}(t-) \geq 1\right\}\right)
$$

again with $\beta_{N^{y}}^{d}$ controlling the dependence on whether there were any past recurrent events. The coefficient values $\beta_{A}^{y}=1.2, \beta_{A}^{d}=0.7$ and $\beta_{A}^{c}=0$ are fixed throughout, and the baseline intensities $\lambda_{\text {baseline }}^{y}, \lambda_{\text {baseline }}^{c}$, and $\lambda_{\text {baseline }}^{d}$ are generated from Weibull distributions. Our main focus is on a primary simulation setting with $\beta_{N^{y}}^{y}=2.1, \beta_{N^{y}}^{d}=1.4$ and $\beta_{N^{y}}^{c}=1.8$, and $\beta_{L_{1}}^{y}=2.1, \beta_{L_{1}}^{d}=0.7$ and $\beta_{L_{1}}^{c}=1.4$, and a secondary simulation setting with independent censoring, i.e., $\beta_{N^{y}}^{c}=\beta_{L_{1}}^{d}=0$. In both these settings, we further consider heterogeneity arising only from dependence on the

past of the recurrent event process, corresponding to the coefficient values $\beta_{L_{1}}^{y}=\beta_{L_{1}}^{d}=\beta_{L_{1}}^{c}=0$. We vary $\alpha^{c} \in \mathbb{R}$ to control the amount of censoring. Further variations over combinations of $\beta_{N^{y}}^{y}, \beta_{N^{y}}^{d}, \beta_{N^{y}}^{c}, \beta_{L_{1}}^{y}, \beta_{L_{1}}^{d}, \beta_{L_{1}}^{c}$ are considered in the Supplementary Material.

We consider estimation of the target parameter $\Psi(P)=\mathbb{E}_{P^{G^{*}}}\left[N^{y}(\tau)\right]$, with $\tau=1.2$, under the simple intervention $\pi^{*}(a \mid \ell)=\mathbb{1}\{a=1\}$, i.e., the target parameter represents the treatmentspecific expected number of recurrent events by time $\tau$.

We consider different estimators for the target parameter as follows: 1. Unadjusted nonparametric estimator. With $\hat{S}_{n}^{d}(\cdot \mid A=1)$ denoting the (stratified) Kaplan-Meier estimator, and $\hat{\Lambda}_{n}^{y}(\cdot \mid A=1)$ denoting the (stratified) Nelson-Aalen estimator, an unadjusted nonparametric estimator for the target parameter is computed as $\hat{\psi}_{n}^{\text {sup }}=\int_{0}^{\tau} \hat{S}_{n}^{d}(t-\mid A=1) \hat{\Lambda}_{n}^{y}(d t \mid A=1)$. 2. Working model based TMLE. With initial estimators based on models for the intensities that leave out the dependence on $N^{y}(t-)$, a working model based TMLE estimator is constructed with a targeting step carried out using estimators for the clever covariates as presented in Section 4.1.1 and by plugging the updated estimators into the formula displayed in (12). 3. TMLE. With initial estimators based on correctly specified models for all intensities, and the targeting step is carried out as outlined in Section 5.1. 4. HAL-TMLE. The HAL-TMLE estimator is constructed as the TMLE estimator, only based on HAL estimators for all intensities. The HAL estimators are here implemented in a simplified version, including (with our notation from Section 6.2) $X=\left(L_{1}, L_{2}, L_{3}, A\right)$ and $V=\mathbb{1}\left\{N^{y}(t-\right) \geq 1\}$.

In the Supplementary Material, to illustrate double robustness, we also consider misspecified models for 2. and 3. that include the linear effect of $L_{1}$ rather than $L_{1}^{2}$ when fitting the model for

the intensity of the distribution of recurrent events.

Figure 1a shows the results from the primary simulation setting with dependent censoring. We verify that our TMLE estimators provide unbiased estimation and appropriate coverage across all variations of low/high censoring and predictiveness of covariates. In contrast, as a result of ignoring follow-up information on the recurrent event process, the working model based TMLE is highly biased across all settings. When heterogeneity arises solely from the dependence on the past of the recurrent event process, we note that the working model based TMLE and the unadjusted nonparametric estimator exhibit very similar performances. The HAL-TMLE does not rely on correct model specification, and demonstrates comparable precision to the correctly specified TMLE.

Figure 1b shows the results from the secondary setting with independent censoring. Here the unadjusted nonparametric estimator yields unbiased estimation, as does the working model based TMLE since the censoring model is correctly specified. Efficiency, as measured by mean squared error, improves in the covariate-dependent setting when using the working model based TMLE, which accounts for predictive covariates, whereas there are no advantages of the working model based TMLE compared to the unadjusted nonparametric estimator in the covariate independent setting. The mean squared error of the (general) TMLE is always better than that of the working model based TMLE, from taking into account the dependence on the past of the recurrent event process. The HAL-TMLE, again, demonstrates comparable performance to the TMLE relying on correctly specified models, with no model specification.

# 8 Real data example 

We illustrate our methods with the dataset readmission obtained from the frailtypack (Rondeau et al., 2012) package in R. These are data from an observational study on readmission (re-

hospitalization) of 403 patients with colorectal cancer (see, González et al., 2005), followed from day of surgery for up to 6 years ( 2176 days). There were 109 deaths, 458 (recurrent) readmission events, and 294 were censored (comprised by migration, change of hospital, or administrative censoring due to different dates of surgery). Several readmissions can occur for the same patient, and, as noted in the original analysis by González et al. (2005), these events are potentially highly dependent, which should be accommodated by the estimation methods for reasons as highlighted in previous sections: 1) if the censoring mechanism depends on the history of the recurrent event process, any method that does not take the general dependence into account is potentially biased, and 2) when the censoring mechanism does not depend on the history of the recurrent event process, methods that do not take the general dependence into account are not efficient.

Based on the data, interest is in assessing the effect of receiving chemotherapy or not, controlling for the available baseline variables: sex, tumour stage, and Charlson's index. We consider the intervention-specific mean outcomes of the number of recurrent events by time $\tau=5$ years (corresponding to 1825 days) under treatment with chemotherapy and no treatment with chemotherapy. The difference between these two intervention-specific mean outcomes represents how many events are on average avoided by the treatment.

In our analysis, we consider (using the same nomenclature as in Section 7) 1) an unadjusted nonparametric estimator, 2) a working model based TMLE estimator, and 3) a HAL-TMLE estimator. For the HAL estimator, we allowed dependence on $N^{y}(t-)$, covariates and chemotherapy through main terms and two-way interactions. We emphasize that the HAL-TMLE estimate is all we are after in the end, and that the other estimates are included solely for reference. Results can

# 9 Discussion 

This work presents targeted learning methodology to estimate the treatment-specific expected number of recurrent events in recurrent events settings with baseline confounding, informative right-censoring, competing risks, and dependence on the recurrent event process. We have presented the efficient influence curve for the estimation problem, as well as its double robust properties, and proposed an estimation procedure based on targeted maximum likelihood estimation with direct plug-in of targeted intensity estimators solving the efficient influence curve equation. Acknowledging the challenges of model misspecification, we have highlighted the incorporation of flexible highly adaptive lasso estimation, allowing us to learn about dependencies in the data without imposing rigid functional forms or interaction assumptions.

It is important to clarify that our sequential procedure is not the same as the longitudinal sequential regression approach, that sequentially performs regression steps across time-points to avoid density estimation Bang and Robins (2005); van der Laan and Gruber (2012); Lendle

et al. (2017). Instead, our sequential procedure serves the purpose of directly evaluating the gcomputation formula for a given density fit. This is similar to the ideas of the previous work on targeted maximum likelihood estimation in discrete-time longitudinal settings (Stitelman et al., 2012), but with subtle differences in how targeting is carried out; while targeting in discrete-time settings can be handled one time-point by one, this is hindered by events happening in continuous time. A key strength of our sequential procedure is its explicit evaluation of the g-computation formula. A limitation, on the other hand, is its relatively slow performance, although we note that the process could straightforwardly be parallelized across subjects to reduce computation time. There are other promising opportunities for future implementations. To estimate the target parameter, one may for example proceed with monte carlo simulations based on the estimators for all the likelihood factors. Alternatively, one could consider using the highly adaptive lasso estimator for all intensities, and evaluate the g-computation formula along the lines of Section 6 without targeting. General theory on the highly adaptive lasso estimator shows that such an estimator can achieve asymptotic efficiency under undersmoothing so that it solves the efficient influence curve equation (van der Laan et al., 2019). It will be of interest to look into whether such an estimator, by leaving out iterative rounds of targeting update steps, may simplify implementation complexity.

In recurrent events settings with presence of death, such as we have considered in this work, it is a well-acknowledged challenge that examining treatment effects only on the recurrent event process can give a misleading impression of the preventative (or causative) nature of the treatment, especially when death rates are high. This is simply due to the fact that individuals can experience

recurrent events only until they encounter the terminal outcome, so that in extreme situations a treatment found to lower the expected number of recurrent events may in fact only do so by increasing mortality. To gain full insights into the effect of a given treatment, estimation could be targeted for multivariate parameters that assess effects jointly on both the expected number of recurrent events and survival probabilities.

abstract:
Longitudinal settings involving outcome, competing risks and censoring events
occurring and recurring in continuous time are common in medical research, but
are often analyzed with methods that do not allow for taking post-baseline
information into account. In this work, we define statistical and causal target
parameters via the g-computation formula by carrying out interventions directly
on the product integral representing the observed data distribution in a
continuous-time counting process model framework. In recurrent events settings
our target parameter identifies the expected number of recurrent events also in
settings where the censoring mechanism or post-baseline treatment decisions
depend on past information of post-baseline covariates such as the recurrent
event process. We propose a flexible estimation procedure based on targeted
maximum likelihood estimation coupled with highly adaptive lasso estimation to
provide a novel approach for double robust and nonparametric inference for the
considered target parameter. We illustrate the methods in a simulation study.
